<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Computing an Allowable Rate of Return on Rate Base
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
I. The Allowable Rate of Return Should Equal the Cost of Capital
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The fundamental objective when using a rate of return on rate base method of regulation is to set a regulated firm's
maximum allowable rate of return on rate base equal to the regulated firm's cost of capital. The cost of capital, sometimes
referred to by economists as ``the opportunity cost of capital'' or ``the required rate of return,'' is the minimum
rate of return necessary to attract capital to an investment. It is the expected rate of return prevailing in capital
markets on alternative investments of equivalent risk.
<FOOTCITE>3</FOOTCITE>
 The bases for setting the allowable rate of return equal to the cost of capital are legal and economic.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
3
