States and Canada Compilation 1992&hyph;1993, National Association of Utility Regulatory Commissioners (``NARUC''),
Washington D.C., 1993, pp. 110&hyph;111. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
</FOOTNOTE>

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The WACC approach recognizes that there are several methods by which a firm may raise capital and each has its attendant
cost. Typically, the total capital of a firm has come from three different sources, long-term debt, preferred stock
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
7
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 and common-stock equity. Thus, the total capital of a firm may have a debt component, a preferred stock component and
a common-stock equity component. Under the WACC methodology,
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
8
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 the cost of each of these components is calculated separately and weighted by the proportion the component is to the
total capital of the firm.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
9
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->

