<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The DCF, CAPM, RP, and MBR methods are market-based approaches that emphasize the standard of capital attraction
articulated in 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Hope
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 and 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Bluefield 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
by examining investors' expectations of the regulated firm's profits, dividends, and 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
market
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 prices. The CE method emphasizes the comparable earnings standard specified by those cases by estimating the return
on 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
book 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
common-stock equity of firms having risk similar to that of the regulated firm under consideration. The five methods
are reviewed in turn. 
